      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Freestanding towel rack</td>
        <td>daily towels where airflow allows</td>
        <td>footprint, stability and drying room</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Removable shower caddy</td>
        <td>current shower products</td>
        <td>support, surface, load and drainage</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Take a move-out view before buying</h2>
  <p>Ask these questions while the room is in use:</p>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Is the change allowed, and is written permission needed?</li>
    <li>Does the product suit the exact surface or support?</li>
    <li>Will it remain stable at the intended loaded weight?</li>
    <li>Can every door, drawer and screen still open?</li>
    <li>Can towels dry and shower shelves drain?</li>
    <li>Can the walls, floor and plumbing still be inspected and cleaned?</li>
    <li>Can the product be removed as directed without damage?</li>
    <li>Would it be useful in another room or the next home?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Make improvements that move with you</h2>
  <p>
    Renter-friendly storage is more than avoiding a drill. It respects the agreement, the
    existing surfaces and the daily movement of the bathroom. It also remains easy to remove
    when the room needs cleaning or the tenancy ends.
  </p>
  <p>
    Start inside the vanity, keep shower storage light, give towels genuine drying room and add
    freestanding furniture only where the floor can spare it. A smaller adaptable piece is
    usually more valuable than a perfect-looking fit that belongs to one address.
  </p>

